The Ball Python Project¶

Alison Qiu¶

The ball python (Python regius) is a snake native to Africa that is so-called due to its tendency to curl into a ball. Likely due to their docile temperament, ball pythons are the most popular pet snake and over 7,500 distinct morphs currently exist. Some of the most commonly recognized morphs are determined by Mendelian dominant or recessive genes, allowing for even more striking phenotypes to result from a combination of such genes. Sometimes, a breeder will breed two snakes with such a dramatic combination of genes that it can become hard to tell exactly which genes are present in the offspring snakes.

You can find a primer on ball python genes here: http://kpexotics.com/Main/2021/08/31/genetic-primer/. Here is the wikipedia page for the snake species in general: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ball_python

The motivation of this project is to explore how ball pythons are priced according to their genes, sex and age, as well as training a neural network to identify the genes present in a ball python given an image of it. Below, I've provided all the imports I've used for the project.

Prelude: Web Scraping¶

Since there aren't very many datasets on ball python images to be found online, I have decided to scrape MorphMarket for images of ball pythons. MorphMarket is a website that allows breeders to list reptiles for sale, and it has a big ball python market. It displays 20 animals per page with a fixed thumbnail size, which keeps the image sizes consistent for when the neural network trains on them.

Selenium is a powerful library that allows you to build your own web scraper. To use it, you call webdriver's browser methods such as Chrome() or Firefox() to open up a crawler in the browser of your choice--I have elected to use Firefox. I will note that before I resorted to Selenium, I had attempted to use BeautifulSoup4 to scrape the listings. However, attempting to search for specific elements, such as snake thumbnail objects, would result in either the desired elements appearing to vanish from the tree or a bunch of unrelated elements being found instead.

You may notice that from looking at documentation for Selenium that a number of different methods for finding web elements--such as 'find_element_by_tag_name' or 'find_element_by_css_selector'--are provided. These methods are for an older version of Selenium and will not work with this version of Python!! Instead, use the newer find_element method, which accepts two arguments--the first of which is the item you are searching on, such as By.TAG_NAME or By.CSS_SELECTOR.

If you have decided to use the CSV files that I've already provided, then you can skip running the web crawler code below. However, if you want to gather your own MorphMarket data, or gather data on different ball python morphs such as albino or pastel, then you'll want to run the code below. The first variable, 'pages_num_pages_csvs', is a list of triples (URL, number of pages, csv name). The web crawler will iterate through the list, opening a new driver for the current URL, then navigating through the specified number of pages. Once it is done moving through the pages, it writes the scraped data into the specified CSV name.

Most sites generally don't appreciate being spammed with requests in a short amount of time. If any client makes too many requests to a server in a short amount of time, the server will often reject further requests with a 403 error. This can mess up the web crawler. I've added in delays between each page and each URL such that the number of requests does not cause MorphMarket to reject the web crawler--the exact values were determined through trial and error.

To gain access to more ball python images, I had the web crawler log in to my MorphMarket account to be able to access historical listings. I have replaced the corresponding fields in the webcrawler code with placeholder strings. You will want to create your own MorphMarket account, then replace the placeholder strings.

A: Training a Neural Network to Recognize Traits in Ball Pythons¶

Part 1: Data Wrangling¶

The way that pandas' to_csv method writes items into a csv file is that it will take the literal string representation of the object and write that into the csv file. While this is sufficient for items such as strings or integers, more complicated objects like images don't have much of their actual information stored in their string representations. Hence, if you are loading the data from the CSVs provided, then you will need to restore the images from the img_url fields given for each snake! I have provided code below to do this.

In [3]:
csvs = ['normals.csv',\
        'single_gene_clowns.csv',\

    snake_df = pd.read_csv(csv, sep='|')
    i = 0
    img_list = list()
    while i < len(snake_df):
        single_snake = snake_df.iloc[i]
        if single_snake['img_url'] != 'https://via.placeholder.com/225x190?text=No+image':
            img = Image.open(BytesIO(requests.get(single_snake['img_url']).content))
        else:
            img = None
        img_list.append(img)
        i = i + 1
    snake_df['img'] = img_list
    df_list.append(snake_df)

The distribution of ball pythons among even the more common morphs suffers from the curse of dimensionality; because multiple morphs can be visually present on a snake, asking a neural network to distinguish between combinations of even just 8 morphs could result in many, many output classes. This is compounded by the fact that some Mendelian dominant morphs have homozygous, or "super" variants, which further complicates things. Hence, I have limited the scope of this project to distinguishing between combinations of three popular morphs: banana, piebald and clown. Below, I've created a dictionary encoding an integer to each combination of morphs.

In [4]:
# Each class is assigned an integer. This is the dictionary mapping integers to classes.

Occasionally, breeders will mistag heterozygous recessive snakes as visuals, or conversely, mistag snakes with extra genes as single-gene snakes. For instance, the 'Piebald' ball python also happens to visually display the albino trait. Sometimes, breeders will also display multiple snakes in one image. The quality of images also tends to vary--some are very professional while others cut out a lot of the snake. Regardless, the vast majority of images should be tagged correctly. The next step in data wrangling will be to bring the data from all eight classes into a single dataframe.

I tried my best to include about 200 images for each class, which is small by image classification standards. However, not all classes have enough snakes, especially the triple gene combo banana clown piebald seeing as such designer combos tend to be far rarer than single-gene or double-gene combos. I do not expect the neural network to be able to classify this last class as well as the other seven. Since seven out of the eight classes are roughly balanced, the risk of the neural network getting stuck at a local minima by guessing a dominant class is relatively low.

For the purposes of image classification, we really only need a couple rows from the united dataframe. However, if you wish to do any future projects, then the additional information such as sex, price, etc. have been made available in my CSV files.

Since the dataset is quite small, we will need to be a little bit sneakier to prevent our model from overfitting to the data. One such technique that I have decided to use is data augmentation. Below, I've defined a data augmentation transformation to randomly flip and rotate snake images in the training set.

In [10]:
data_augmentation = tf.keras.Sequential([
  layers.RandomFlip("horizontal_and_vertical"),
  layers.RandomRotation(0.2),
])

Part 2: Training the Neural Network¶

Now that we have prepared the training dataset, it's time to create the neural network. For the purposes of this project, I've decided to use the pre-trained neural network Xception, which is available from Keras. It will be frozen (prevented from updating) while I'll add a couple extra layers for our specific task.

The dense layer will be able to see the features extracted by the Xception model, then learn how to classify the ball pythons. The dropout layer is another guard against overfitting. Since there are eight classes to classify amongst, I've chosen to output eight neurons and use the softmax activation function, which outputs the probability that a given image belongs to each class.

I should note that the design of neural networks is largely an art form at the moment. I had gone through many different architectures before I settled upon this approach. Here's a source explaining how exactly to make a convolutional neural network in Keras: https://towardsdatascience.com/building-a-convolutional-neural-network-cnn-in-keras-329fbbadc5f5

In [55]:
# Loading in the Xception model.
transfer_model = Sequential(name="Transfer-Ball-Python-Model")
transfer_model.add(keras.applications.Xception(
    weights='imagenet',  # Load weights pre-trained on ImageNet.
    input_shape=(augmented_X_train.shape[1], augmented_X_train.shape[2], augmented_X_train.shape[3]),
    include_top=False))  # Do not include the ImageNet classifier at the top.

# Now adding in my own layers for this classification problem.
transfer_model.add(Flatten(name="Transfer-Flatten-layer"))
transfer_model.add(Dense(128, activation='leaky_relu', name='Hidden-Layer-1', kernel_initializer='HeNormal')) # Hidden Layer, relu(x) = max(x, 0)
transfer_model.add(Dropout(0.3, name='Dropout-3'))
transfer_model.add(Dense(8, activation='softmax', name='Output-Layer')) # Output Layer, softmax(x) = exp(x) / tf.reduce_sum(exp(x))

# Freezing the Xception layer.
transfer_model.layers[0].trainable=False

While designing my model and testing it, I found SGD to be a better optimizer than 'Adam', as the loss for Adam would often times 'explode' or have my neural network be stuck at 'guess all the snakes to be banana clowns'. However, if the learning rate is too high for stochastic gradient descent, the loss may diverge altogether and become 'nan', which will inevitably 'kill' the neural network.

Because the output is encoded as a single integer that may take on eight different forms--rather than eight one-hot-encoded columns--the correct loss function to use here is 'sparse_categorical_crossentropy'. If the target values were to be one-hot-encoded, you would use the regular 'categorical_crossentropy' loss function instead.

The metric being used here is 'sparse_categorical_accuracy', which is specifically designed for this type of output. However, you can also use the regular 'accuracy' metric.

Part 3: Analysis of the Performance of the Neural Network¶

The test data has a notably lower accuracy than the train data, which indicates that the model is overfit. Despite this, the model is still far better at predicting the correct morphs than randomly guessing.

I notice that in particular, category "2" (single gene piebalds) seems to have an unusually low recall, while category "3" (clown piebalds) appears to have an unusually low precision. I suspect that these two categories are getting confused with each other because the model will eagerly label snakes in either category as clown piebalds.

We can visualize the labels that the model is predicting for ball python images using the same subplots feature as above, with some minor tweaks.

Sometimes, the neural network will predict a mismatch of labels for a snake, even though the original label was wrong in the first place! For instance, the 'banana piebald' ball python in the bottom middle cell is actually het for piebald (no visual piebald), so it would be correct for the neural network to predict 'banana'.

It seems that the neural network tends to confuse clown ball pythons and non-clown ball pythons in general. Clown ball pythons mistaken for being normal ball pythons are dark in color, whereas normal ball pythons mistaken for being clown tend to be brighter in color. Instead of learning that clown ball pythons have a specific pattern mutation setting them apart, the neural network has seen that clowns happen to "appear" brighter in color since the clown morph has less of the dark color than the nonclown morph.

I am particularly interested in which classes are confused with each other. For instance, running the code fragment above several times tends to indicate that classes that include the banana gene tend to get confused with other classes in their group. Classes that include the "piebald" morph tended to get mistaken for the corresponding class that lacks piebald--so a banana piebald ball python might get mistaken for a regular banana, or a regular piebald might get mistaken as being a normal snake.

Below, I have written code to investigate which classes are getting confused with others.

While all non-nan listings have a birth year, not all listings have a birthday or even a birth month. I will fill in the missing days and missing months as "7" and "July", respectively. Then, we can convert all the birth dates to number of days old.

In [29]:
from datetime import datetime
today = datetime.now()
price_age_df['missing_month'] = price_age_df['preprocessedbirth'].apply(lambda x: 'July ' + x if re.search('^[0-9]{4}$', x) is not None else x)
price_age_df['missing_day'] = price_age_df['missing_month'].apply(lambda x: '7 ' + x if re.search('^[a-zA-Z]* [0-9]{4}$', x) is not None else x)
price_age_df['datetime'] = price_age_df['missing_day'].apply(lambda x: datetime.strptime(x, '%d %B %Y'))
price_age_df['days_old'] = price_age_df['datetime'].apply(lambda x: (today - x).days)

Part 2: Data Exploration¶

I would like to see how the different attributes of a ball python affect its price, such as sex, age and traits. We can create a linear regression of the data including attributes as interaction terms.

Now that we have a numeric value for how old a ball python is, we can plot a scatter plot of ball python ages versus prices to see if there's a clear relationship.

In [30]:
plt.scatter(price_age_df['days_old'], price_age_df['numeric_price'])
plt.title('Scatterplot of ball python ages vs prices', fontsize='large')
plt.xlabel('Days old', fontsize='large')
plt.ylabel('Price (USD)', fontsize='large')

linear_regressor = LinearRegression()  # create object for the class
linear_regressor.fit(price_age_df['days_old'].values.reshape(-1, 1), price_age_df['numeric_price'].values.reshape(-1, 1))  # perform linear regression
Y_pred = linear_regressor.predict(price_age_df['days_old'].values.reshape(-1, 1))  # make predictions
plt.plot(price_age_df['days_old'].values.reshape(-1, 1), Y_pred, color='red')
print("coefficient", linear_regressor.coef_[0][0])
print("intercept", linear_regressor.intercept_[0])

coefficient 0.5128102314466285
intercept 697.2601626784286

It appears that most snakes tend to be relatively young. Additionally, there isn't an obvious relationship between age and price. No snake that is older than about 2500 days has a price above 2000, but despite this, the linear regression has predicted a positive relationship between age and price. Let's see if other attributes will bring more clarity to the situation.

In the ball python breeding industry, female ball pythons are more valued than male ball pythons because a male ball python takes far less time to successfully reproduce than a female does. Let's visualize the distribution of prices by sex. Seaborn includes functions that allow you to easily make box plots, violin plots and more.

Earlier, we had one-hot encoded traits as integer values. We can predict a linear regression with not just price, but also including traits and sex as interaction terms. For each term, I will arbitrarily set a P-value of 0.05. This P-value means that if the chances of obtaining a particular event are less than 0.05, then I should reject the null hypothesis claiming that there is no relationship between the price of a ball python and its other attributes.

Every single variable that we tested on has a P-value less than 0.05! In fact, all of them save for 'isBanana' have a P-value of approximately 0. In addition, the P-value of the F-statistic is so small that it is essentially 0. Hence we can more or less reject the null hypothesis that breeders do not take these variables into account when deciding the price of their snakes.

The more interesting information comes from the exact coefficients that each variable imparts. The variables with the highest coefficients were isClown and isPiebald at approximately 1500 USD each; snakes with these traits on average were worth 1500USD more than snakes without these traits. isBanana, on the other hand, only gives a snake about 127 USD more in value. This makes more sense when taking into consideration how these genes manifest; clown and piebald are Mendelian recessive and only manifest if a snake has two copies of the gene, while banana is Mendelian dominant and will manifest as long as a snake has at least one copy of the gene. Therefore, a snake visually displaying clown or piebald is "harder" to get than a snake visually displaying banana.

Whether or not a snake was listed as female also influenced its price; female snakes are worth approximately 432 USD more than other snakes. This wasn't worth as much as whether or not a snake is visually clown or piebald, but worth more than whether or not a snake is visually banana. This sort of makes sense when considering that ball pythons hatching from a clutch have a 50/50 chance of being male or female regardless of the traits they possess, so female ball pythons aren't hard to produce compared to visual clowns or piebalds.

C: Conclusion¶

Throughout this project, we scraped ball python data from MorphMarket, trained a neural network on image data, and finally explored the relationship between price and other attributes of a snake. It is very possible to get a neural network to learn what the different traits of ball pythons look like, and have it achieve a decent accuracy in predicting the correct label. However, this task suffers from the curse of dimensionality as listed above, as well as the 'slowness' in new listings of more exotic trait combinations being posted. In addition, the bar plots of mislabelled snakes by class revealed an unexpected epiphany: clown piebalds and regular piebalds are colored very similarly. In the future, with more resources and data, a neural network might be able to distinguish between many morphs and combinations thereof.

As for exploring the relationship between price and other attributes, it comes as no surprise to me that some of the variation in price can be explained by the sex, traits and age of a snake. The specific effects each variable had on price were more interesting and reveal a "hierarchy" of sorts to the values that breeders put on attributes; recessive visuals had a much higher value than dominant visuals or the snake being female, even though the latter two traits also have a positive impact on the price of a snake.

Overall, I learned more than expected when I was doing this project on ball pythons. I hope you've learned something new and interesting about these funny snakes and that you've come to appreciate them some more.
